        <tr>
          <td colspan="2"><span
class="postbody">Hello ladies and gents, I’m here to tell you all a story about the ranger’s plight.  In the many words to come I would like to present a detailed analysis of the ranger’s damage to gold ratio.  Why am I comparing my combat damage dealt to gold you ask?  Quite simply it pays not to be a ranger.  There are many things that cost me and other rangers exuberant amounts of funding.  Narrowing the scope down to the main three: provisions, arrows, and poisons I would now like to share how I feel about all of this.  Seeing as how provisions are not a cost specific to rangers I will omit that for the sake of argument.  
<br />

<br />
Moving right along to arrows let me present to you this.  How many other classes are paying to deal damage in combat?  Everything will be all right though.  Rangers all come pre-equipped with a skill called Makeshift Arrows.  Properly labeled, this skill is only useful in situations where I wish to throw away my power frivolously.  Not using the best arrows in the game is simply not an option.  A ranger who heads into a battle without the best arrows equipped is an assassin of approximately the 40th level.  
<br />

<br />
Knowing that my class is lacking in dps I did what any curious ranger, who is desperately searching for a way to fit in, might do.  I went to town and bought a stack of each type of the most expensive arrows I could find.  I figured I may as well go the extra mile, so I also called upon some of the server’s most well known woodworkers and employed them towards my ends.    Keep in mind here that for a stack(99) of each type of arrow I have just now paid 2.5gold for store-bought ones, and 5 gold a stack for the player-made arrows.  
<br />

<br />
Having completed all my town errands I shortly thereafter sought out some mobs with which I may test my newfound arrows.  I wanted to go pick on some low-ac mobs so as to test the high end range of my skills.  The skill I will be mentioning from this point on concerning arrows is better known as “Culling the Herd”, a level 44 ranger skill that costs 99 power to use.  Before testing out my supposedly uber arrows, I whip out my bow and take a shot at the newbie mites in the Antonica farmlands.   I consistently land shots for around 400-450 dmg and my skill is adept 1.  That isn’t very good dmg, but I have yet to test out my shiny new and improved arrows.  I whip out a couple and start landing shots for around 550-600 dmg.  Elated at my having found a new way by which I can add more damage to a raid party, I shoot off a few more arrows.  Before I know it I’ve gone through a whole stack.  Looking back on what I’ve just done I slowly realize how much money I just tossed away plucking arrows at newbie mobs.  I just spent 3 gold on a stack of arrows!  Sure it could be said that I shouldn’t be wasting all these good arrows on newbie mobs, but the sad reality of the matter is that I have to use these arrows if I wish to do any real damage against epic mobs and exp mobs alike.  
<br />

<br />
My best single target bowshot has been known to do around 1000 dmg, but only in very extreme raid type situations when everyone and their cousins have debuffs in on the target.  On top of the mob being debuffed beyond recognition, I must have already equipped arrows that cost roughly three silver a piece.  Three silver a piece!!!  Why would anyone complain about tossing away three silver on an arrow to do 1000 dmg!??  Well, considering I shoot out anywhere from 300-600 arrows on the average raid night, that’s quite a bit of pocket change.  To spare you the crazy multi-variable calculus work that’s anywhere from 9 to 18 gold on any given night.  Keep in mind this is if I am buying only the store-bought ones.  If I want to change up my arrow type by purchasing arrows from a woodworker this cost will increase to a whopping 15 to 30 gold.  It is true all rangers are crazy rich because of their uncanny ability to solo *laugh*, but this type of negative cash flow does seem to catch up with me at times.  Let me ask once more.  Who else is paying approximately 15 gold a night to still remain a lackluster dps in a raid?
<br />

<br />
Poisons are great.  I love the idea of poisons.  Regardless of the fact that nearly all raid mobs I have encounteredd say, “Pffft, silly ranger!!!  You know I am quasi-resistant to any and all poison variants you can come up with!!!111”, I still love the concept.  Poisons do in fact help me out a lot concerning dps issues in exp groups, but they do nothing for me in raids.  This is however not a post about poisons, but rather about rangers and their cost effectiveness.  At 15 silver a hit, and about a hit every 20 minutes.  On any given raid night I am looking at spending another 3-5 gold.  This cost is only truly applicable to raids where many exp-group mobs must be cleared to reach the raid encounters.  All in all I am now staring at a bill of about 12 to 35 gold per raid night solely because I am a ranger.  
<br />

<br />
Now I don’t want to get all caught up in a class dps comparison because the other classes out there who are proficient at invoking death amongst their enemies should stay that way.  I do not intend for other classes to lose their edge in order for the ranger to feel more powerful, but rather it is my hope that the ranger will be addressed.  Truth of the matter is that a well-geared ranger, with top quality arrows, and with top quality poisons, is still only putting out as much damage as an assassin who is only half-heartedly playing the game.  Being a sad dps class is one thing, but being charged for it at the same time is a whole other issue.  
<br />

<br />
I don’t want to leave this an open-ended, whining post about how rangers are the way they are, but rather give some suggestions as to how we may become more like what I believe we were intended to be.  
<br />

<br />
First and foremost, fix the Steady Aim/Take Aim/Focus Fire skill line that rangers have.  What do rangers have that make them more special at archery than other classes?  As it stands right now they have nothing.  These skills are supposed to add to “ranged” skill, and if I am reading correctly should also last 15 minutes as they fall into the self-buff category.  This skill line, instead of adding to ranged, is adding to “bow”.  What does “bow” skill do?  Like many other weapon-oriented skills, the higher the “bow” skill, the higher level ranged weapon I can equip.  When I activate Focus Fire now it adds 55 points to my bow skill for 36 seconds.  This means that for 36 seconds I can equip a required skill 305 bow.  That is obviously not working.  Another yet smaller issue concerning this skill is the scale of how many points it is adding.  I used to have adept 1 which added 50 points of bow skill.  Foreseeing the possible usefulness of this skill were it ever to be corrected I sought out the master version.  Money aside, the master 1 version of Focus Fire is adding a whopping 5 more points to my bow skill.  What can be done here?  Fix this skill to add to my “ranged” arts instead of my “bow” skill.  This would increase the ranger’s effectiveness in ranged combat essentially making them a level 61 ranger.  This is the answer rangers are looking for concerning all bow-related issues.  Fixing a skill like this would truly make the ranger the most proficient ranged-combat artist.  
<br />

<br />
My second suggestion for ranger fixes would require an overhaul of all ranger bow skills.  As a level 50 ranger who has put quite some time into his character in many different situations I find that there are only two, and a possible third useful bow skill. In order of importance these are Culling the Herd(bowshot backstab), Storm of Arrows(Area Effect bowshot), and Hidden Fire(high damage shot requiring stealth).  One other skill, Triple Fire, would be useful if I was not paying ten silver per use.  Because of this cost I completely disregard the effectiveness of the skill.  Concerning the high cost maintaining an arrow supply, I am very hard pressed to find any other bow skills that are useful in any situation.  They just simply have no use.  
<br />
	
<br />
In short, while paying it out the ass for arrows and poisons is a real pain, I will continue to do so provided that it is a worthwhile necessity.  Perhaps something can be done to curb the costs of battle, or allow rangers to better supply themselves, but that is an issue that will take much time and consideration on the part of the development team.  The most cost-effective fix I see coming to rangers would be properly implementing the Focus Fire skill line.  Were Focus Fire to be addressed properly, I believe rangers of all levels would from that point forward be able to proudly maintain the title of Ranged Masters.  
<br />

<br />
Thank you to all who have taken the time out of your lives to read what all I have had to say, and to those who have not, I apologize for the lengthiness of the post.  
<br />

<br />
Ever so sincerely,
<br />
Poyzin</span><span
class="gensmall"></span></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
  </tr>
