        <tr>
          <td colspan="2"><span
class="postbody">Sounds like you've got serious problems.  I expected Rangers to be really expensive to play, but do really good damage.  If they can't keep up with assassins even when spending boatloads for arrows, there's clearly a problem.  That -slashing ac debuff looks like pure ass compared to the debuffs of swashes and brigands; do assassins get one way better than that as well?
<br />

<br />
Did want to comment on one thing:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Poyzin wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">First and foremost, fix the Steady Aim/Take Aim/Focus Fire skill line that rangers have.  What do rangers have that make them more special at archery than other classes?  As it stands right now they have nothing.  These skills are supposed to add to “ranged” skill, and if I am reading correctly should also last 15 minutes as they fall into the self-buff category.  This skill line, instead of adding to ranged, is adding to “bow”.  What does “bow” skill do?  Like many other weapon-oriented skills, the higher the “bow” skill, the higher level ranged weapon I can equip.  When I activate Focus Fire now it adds 55 points to my bow skill for 36 seconds.  This means that for 36 seconds I can equip a required skill 305 bow.  That is obviously not working.  Another yet smaller issue concerning this skill is the scale of how many points it is adding.  I used to have adept 1 which added 50 points of bow skill.  Foreseeing the possible usefulness of this skill were it ever to be corrected I sought out the master version.  Money aside, the master 1 version of Focus Fire is adding a whopping 5 more points to my bow skill.  What can be done here?  Fix this skill to add to my “ranged” arts instead of my “bow” skill.  This would increase the ranger’s effectiveness in ranged combat essentially making them a level 61 ranger.  This is the answer rangers are looking for concerning all bow-related issues.  Fixing a skill like this would truly make the ranger the most proficient ranged-combat artist.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I was under the impression that increasing the skill for a specific weapon type increases the effective level at which you use that weapon; IE if you're level 50, and you get your bow skill bumped to up 305, you're effectively level 61 for basic bow usage.  This should (I think) cause two things to happen:
<br />

<br />
- basic bow damage increases as appropriate if you're using a bow you haven't mastered yet (so if you're 50 you'd need a bow with over 250 skill to master to see any bonus from this, and I don't know if any such bows exist)
<br />
- unmastered bow-based CA damage increases; for this I suspect you will also need both a higher skill level bow (so the bow itself doesn't cap your effectiveness) AND the ability to increase your Archery skill, and I don't know if you have a CA for that.  
<br />

<br />
For the second one I don't really know if you'd need to increase your bow skill level to uncap unmastered CA damage, so it might be right out.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I'm sorta just speculating on those, I haven't personally tested the particular mechanics (which is something I usually do before commenting on em).  My bruiser is a few % from getting a +Physicality ability, but I can't use it in conjunction with my +Fist ability, so I can't really test how they interact.  Some bruisers apparently love the +Fist ability, but I haven't found any good fist weapons at my level so I've ignored it.</span><span
class="gensmall"></span></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </td>
  </tr>
